The people of Macedonia voted in a referendum on Sunday on whether to change the name of their country to “Republic of Northern Macedonia”, which would resolve a long-standing dispute with Greece, which blocked its applications for membership in the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which includes the province of Macedonia, claims that the name of its northern neighbour is a claim to its territory, and vetoed its accession to NATO and the EU.
In June, both Governments concluded an agreement based on the proposal of a new name, but the nationalist opponents argue that this change would undermine the ethnic identity of the Slavic majority of the Macedonian population.
President Giorgi Ivanov stated that he would not vote in the referendum, and the boycott campaign questioned whether voter turnout would be within the 50 per cent minimum required for the referendum.
The question put to the referendum was as follows: “Do you support NATO and EU membership, subject to the adoption of a treaty with Greece?”
Supporters of name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that Macedonia, one of the countries that emerged after Yugoslavia’s dissolution, should pay the price for joining organizations such as the EU and NATO.
“I came today to vote for the future of the country, for the young people of Macedonia, so that they can live freely under the auspices of the European Union, because it means a safer life for all of us,” says 79-year-old Oliver of George, a resident of Skopje.
A sufficient number of members of Parliament stated that they would respect the outcome of the vote in order to make it decisive, although it was not legally binding.
A change of name would require a two-thirds majority of the members of Parliament.
The State Electoral Commission stated that no violations had been reported by 1:00 p.m.
However, the turnout was only 16 per cent, compared with 34 per cent in the last parliamentary elections in 2016, when 66 per cent of registered voters voted.
“I came to vote for my children, our place in Europe,” says 62-year-old Yose Tanevski, a voter from the capital Skopje.
The Prime Minister of Macedonia, Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and his son Duško voted in favour of a referendum in Macedonia on changing the name of the country, which will open the way for her to join NATO and the European Union in Strumica, Macedonia, on 30 September 2018.
In front of the parliament building in Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, age 54, prepared a small scene by placing chairs in front of tents set by those citizens who are going to boycott the referendum.
“We are in favour of NATO and EU membership, but we want to unite with our head held high, rather than the floors of the cabinets,” Kawadarkov says.
“Yes, we are citizens of a poor country, but we also have a sense of self-esteem.
If they do not want to accept us as Macedonia, we can turn to other countries, such as China and Russia, and become part of Euro-Asian integration.”
Prime Minister Zaev said that NATO membership would bring the investments in Macedonia that were so necessary in that country, where the unemployment rate was over 20 per cent.
“I believe that the overwhelming majority will be in favour, because more than 80 per cent of our citizens support the EU and NATO,” Zaev said after the vote.
He believes that a positive response will be “a pledge to our prosperous future”.
A survey published last Monday by the Institute of Political Studies of Macedonia revealed that between 30 and 43 per cent of voters would participate in the referendum, but that was below the required turnout.
Another survey conducted by the Macedonian Telecom-TV revealed that 57 per cent of respondents planned to vote on Sunday.
