Throughout Bolivia, which is landlocked, the memory of the coastline lost to Chile as a result of the bloody conflict of the 19th century over resources is still alive; it is alive and eager to sail again in the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes may have been the bravest in decades, as Bolivia awaits the decision of an international court on 1 October as a result of five years of debate.
“Bolivia has energy, a spirit of unity and a balance of mind, and, of course, there is a positive outcome,” said Bolivian diplomat Roberto Calzadilla.
Many Bolivians will be watching the decision-making process at the International Court of Justice on large screens throughout the country, hoping that the tribunal at The Hague will be able to support Bolivia ' s statement that, after decades of intense negotiations, Chile is obliged to negotiate a sovereign access to the sea for Bolivia.
Evo Morales, the charismatic indigenous President of Bolivia, who is fighting a difficult battle for re-election next year, is also anxiously awaiting a decision to be delivered on Monday.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific,” he argued at the end of August.
However, some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to decide in favour of Bolivia, and if it does, it will make little difference.
