John Edward: Knowledge of languages is of great importance to the citizens of the world
Independent schools in Scotland continue their tradition of brilliant education, which was reaffirmed in 2018: the outstanding results of the examinations have demonstrated individual and collective success in sports, arts, music and other socially significant disciplines.
These schools are part of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), with more than 30,000 students all over Scotland seeking to provide the highest level of services for pupils and their parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their pupils for further higher education, their career choices and the status of citizens of the world.
As part of the education sector, which is responsible for developing and implementing an individual school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and desirable in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, you call to his mind.
If you speak to him in his native language, you speak to his heart.”
This is a strong indication that we cannot rely solely on English if we want to build relationships with and trust citizens of other countries.
From this year ' s latest examinations, we see that languages are at the forefront of the league tables and have the highest score in independent schools.
A total of 68 per cent of pupils who studied foreign languages received the highest “A” rating.
Data from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 per cent of pupils received "A" in Mandarin (Chinese non-meaning), while 72 per cent of students in German, 69 per cent in French and 63 per cent in Spanish also received "A".
This proves that in independent schools in Scotland foreign languages are clearly considered vital for children and young people in the future.
Language subjects are now in the same demand as natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curricula of independent schools and other educational institutions.
A survey conducted by the British Commission on Employment and Skills in 2014 found that among the reasons that made it difficult for employers to fill vacancies, 17 per cent were due to language skills.
Language skills are thus increasingly becoming the key to a successful future career for young people.
Given that more promising jobs require language skills, these skills are needed in a globalized world.
No matter what profession the pupil chooses, if he learns a second language, he will gain a real advantage in the future by learning another additional skill that will be useful for him throughout his life.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a person who knows more than one foreign language a competitive advantage.
According to a YouTube survey in which over 4,000 British adults participated in 2013, 75 per cent were unable to speak English well enough to support conversation, and French was the only language with a double-digit percentage, with 15 per cent of respondents speaking it.
That is why investing in language education is so relevant now.
Knowledge of several languages, especially those of developing economies, would give children a better chance of finding a good job.
Scotland has a wide range of languages that are taught — each school has a different set of languages.
A number of schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered most important to Britain in the light of the future of the country until 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of your child, independent schools will always have a choice of several languages with teaching staff whose members are specialists in these languages.
Independent schools in Scotland seek to create an environment that will train children and equip them with the skills necessary to succeed, regardless of their future.
At present, it cannot be denied that languages remain vital for the future development of the country in the global business environment, and this should therefore be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages need to be seen as “skills of international communication”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, which provides diversity and benefits for Scottish youth.
Il faut ben le faire.
John Edwards, Director, Board of Independent Schools of Scotland
