North Korea says that “adamantly” will not be unilaterally disarmed without trust
The Foreign Minister of North Korea had stated at the United Nations on Saturday that the ongoing sanctions increased mistrust of the United States and that his country would under no circumstances renounce its nuclear weapons unilaterally.
Ri Young-ho stated at the annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “significant measures of good will” last year, such as the cessation of nuclear and missile tests, the dismantling of the nuclear test site and the commitment not to build up nuclear weapons and not to develop nuclear technology.
“However, we are not seeing a symmetrical reaction from the United States,” he said.
“Without confidence in the US, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances we will not be the first to take unilateral action on disarmament.”
While Ri repeated North Korea's previous complaints about Washington's “step-by-step” approach to denuclearization, according to which North Korea would be rewarded for progressive steps, his statement seemed important in the sense that it had not rejected unilateral denuclearization without control, as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to the joint statement made by Kim Jong Eun and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between the incumbent US President and the North Korean leader, which took place in Singapore on 12 June, when Kim promised to start a movement towards “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula”, and Trump promised security assurances to North Korea.
North Korea seeks to formally end the Korean War of 1950-53, but the United States states that Pyongyang must first renounce its nuclear weapons.
Washington also resists calls to ease severe international sanctions against North Korea.
“The U.S. insists that “denuclearization must take place first” and increases the level of pressure through sanctions to enforce its purpose, and even opposes the “declaration of the end of war”, says Re.
“The notion that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a utopian dream of people who don't know us.
But the real problem is that the ongoing sanctions increase our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention the plans for the second Kim-Trump summit, which the US leader mentioned at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the Minister focused on three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea, not the US, was the party to this issue of denuclearization, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be in such a deadlock.”
However, the tone of Ri’s speech differed sharply from that of last year when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting North Korea’s missiles on the US mainland was inevitable after “Mr. President of Evil” Trump called Kim “a suicide rocket.”
