Harvard students go on vacation in special courses
The new course introduced this year at Harvard University has helped all elementary students to learn to sleep more and to fight the chauvinist culture of continuous caffeine consumption in order to stay awake overnight.
One of the academics found that the world’s most successful students often have no idea how to take care of themselves.
Charles Chaisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed a course that, in his view, is the first of its kind in the United States.
After his opening, he was caught up in the idea of introducing such a course, giving a preliminary report on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning processes.
“At the end of my report, a girl approached me and said, ‘It’s a shame that I only learned about it now that I’m about to graduate.’
She said that no one had ever told her the importance of sleep — which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was first offered to students this year, shows how a healthy sleep habits contribute to academic and sports performance, as well as how it improves the general well-being of the individual.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and CEO of the University's Health Service, said that the university had decided to introduce the course after it had been determined that the students suffered from a serious sleep deficit during the school week.
The class lasts one hour and students perform a number of interactive assignments.
One section of the class offers an image of the dormitory room, where students press coffee cups, curtains, simulators, and books to learn how each of these actions and substances — coffee, the light that causes sleep deprivation — affects sports outcomes, and how important it is to get enough sleep every day.
In another section, participants learn how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
The interactive map of campus encourages participants to think about their daily lives.
“We understand that these classes will not change the behaviour of students at once.
But we believe that they have a right to know, just as any other person has a right to know, for example, how smoking affects his health,” added Professor Chaisler.
According to him, the false sense of pride that a person can “sniff all night” is still quite widespread, and modern technology, as is the growing pressure on students, means that sleep deprivation is becoming a problem.
He said that enough sleep of good quality was a student’s “secret weapon” to cope with stress, nervous exhaustion and anxiety, and even to control overweight, as lack of sleep puts the brain in a state of starvation, making it constantly hungry.
Raymond Soe, a 19-year-old California student in chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Chaser develop the course by attending one of his first years at Harvard last year.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to spread this information throughout campus.
He hoped that the next step would be to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar training programme before entering a competitive educational institution.
Professor Chaisler recommends that students install an alarm clock that warns them to go to sleep and wake up, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lamps, which disrupts the human biothythmology and leads to problems with falling asleep.
