National Trust is listening to the secret life of bats.
A new study carried out in one of the highlands of Scotland is designed to show how bats use the landscape in search of food.
It is hoped that the data obtained will provide a new perspective on the behaviour of unique winged mammals and will help to further the conservation of the species.
A study organized by scientists at the National Foundation of Scotland will examine common non-sophies, non-soprano, and brown long-haired bats and Dobanton nightstands in Inverwewe Gardens, Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be installed at some locations around the site to monitor bat activity throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile site surveys using manual detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all records will determine the frequency of screams as well as the activities for which different groups of these animals are responsible.
A map of the environment will then be drawn up and a report prepared to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour on the scale of the landscape.
Rob Dewar, the NTS conservation adviser, hopes that these results will show which habitats are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to identify key areas of habitat management, such as grassland formation, as well as ways to maintain forest areas in a state that is optimal for bats and other related species.
The population of bats in Scotland and throughout the UK has declined significantly over the last century.
They are threatened with extinction because of the construction and development work that affects their habitat and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting installations can be dangerous, as can sticky fly tape, chemical treatment of building materials and hunting of pet cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, their night hunting habits are such that their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They're using sophisticated echo-location techniques to pinpoint the obstacles to flight.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, takes the population of bats very seriously.
The organization has 10 trained experts who conduct regular interviews, on-site checks and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization even created the first and only Bat Reserve in Scotland at the Threave Manor in Dumfries and Gallowey, where eight out of ten species of Scottish bats live.
Real estate manager David Thompson says the estate is the perfect place for them.
"Here, in Threave, a great place for bats," he says.
“There are old buildings, many old trees and all elements of a good habitat.
But much about bats remains unknown, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us to better understand what they need for a successful existence.”
He recalled the importance of screening for bats before maintenance within private domains, since the unintentional destruction of one nest could lead to the death of up to 400 females and young people, and possibly even to the destruction of the entire local population.
Bats are protected by law, their destruction, harassment or destruction of their habitats are illegal.
Elizabeth Ferrelle, a Scottish bat conservation officer, is calling for public help.
She says, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and we just don't know how many of their individual species live."
