How the Trade War with America Can Be Useful for Beijing
Experts believe that the first waves of the US-China trade war were deafening, and while the battle is far from over, divisions between countries can benefit Beijing in the long run.
Donald Trump, the President of the United States, issued his first warning earlier this year, taxing China’s major exports, including solar panels, steel, and aluminium.
The most significant escalation occurred this week, when new tariffs affected products worth $200 billion (150 billion pounds), effectively taxing half of all goods coming from China to the US.
Beijing has responded in an equivalent way each time, recently imposing $60 billion in duties on United States goods, ranging from 5 to 10 per cent.
China has promised that the response against the US will be equal every time, and the second-largest economy of the world is unlikely to face any difficulties in the near future.
To force Washington to retreat is to yield to demands, but publicly to yield to the US would be too shameful for Xi Jinping, China’s president.
Nevertheless, experts believe that if Beijing is able to play its cards properly, the pressure of the US trade war can provide long-term support to China by reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
“The fact that a quick political decision in Washington or Beijing could create conditions that would lead to economic stumps in any of these countries is, in fact, far more dangerous than previously acknowledged by observers,” says Abigail Grace, a researcher at the Center for New American Security, specializing in Asia.
The Minister for Foreign Affairs stated that Syria was “ready” for the return of refugees
