Red tide: The news has decreased the concentration of micro-organisms in Pinellas, Manati and Sarasota
The latest report of the Florida Commission for Fish and Wildlife shows an overall decrease in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to FWC, in the districts of Pinellas, Manati, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, there are reports of abundant blooms, indicating a decrease in the concentration of micro-organisms.
The red tide extends approximately 130 miles of coastline from northern Pinell to southern Lee counties.
The ochagi can be seen about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsboro County, but their number has declined significantly since last week.
The red tide is also found in Pasco County.
Last week, average concentrations were reported in and around Pinellas County, from low to high concentrations in the coastal area of Hillsboro District, high concentrations in Manati and Sarasota districts and coastal areas, medium concentrations in Charlotte County, high concentrations in Li County and low concentrations in Collier County.
In the districts of Pinellas, Manati, Sarasota, Lee and Collier, there is still a risk of respiratory irritation.
No such possibility was reported in Northwestern Florida last week.
